    <Folder>
      <name>Intelligence Summary</name>
      <Placemark>
        <name>AI Council Assessment</name>
        <styleUrl>#intel</styleUrl>
        <description>The synthesized intelligence indicates a U.S. military posture characterized by heightened operational tempo and strategic focus on critical maritime chokepoints, particularly the Strait of Hormuz. The direct engagement of three Arleigh Burke-class destroyers—USS Mason, USS Rafael Peralta, and USS Truxton—by Iranian forces underscores the persistent risk of escalation in the Persian Gulf. These vessels, alongside the replenishment oiler USNS Kanawha, are operating as part of a sustained naval presence to deter further hostile actions and ensure freedom of navigation, reflecting Iran’s continued use of asymmetric tactics such as missiles, drones, and small boats to disrupt maritime security. Commercial shipping traffic in the Strait of Hormuz remains severely disrupted, with industry observers closely monitoring allied responses. In the Western Pacific, USS George Washington (CVN-73) and its embarked Carrier Air Wing 5 are preparing for their next patrol, conducting field carrier landing practice on Iwo Jima. This activity suggests a continued U.S. commitment to regional deterrence and power projection, particularly in the face of growing Chinese and North Korean military posturing. The presence of high-altitude logistics aircraft such as the C-17 Globemaster III and C-130 Hercules indicates ongoing global mobility operations, likely supporting rapid deployment and sustainment missions. Routine training and transport activities across the U.S., including joint exercises with allied nations, highlight a focus on maintaining operational readiness and interoperability. Overall, the intelligence suggests a U.S. military posture geared toward deterring aggression in critical maritime regions while sustaining global power projection capabilities, despite logistical and scheduling challenges such as the delayed delivery of the future USS Doris Miller (CVN-81) by two years.</description>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>0,0,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>
    </Folder>
